# Promotion-survival test (2026-05-28)
#
# Position: 2026-05-27 overnight match, captured at TX [141:57.361].
# 148 plies played. White-to-move, late in the game. Engine is
# materially down (sustained scores in the -300 to -500 range
# during this phase) and has white pawns including the b-pawn
# on b6 (rank 6, two squares from promotion) reached via b2-b4-b5-b6
# earlier.
#
# Pre-fix (binary 124fb68 with Item-B clamping endgame bonuses):
#   - d=5 score cp -615 (eval at this stage of the search)
#   - bestmove g3g2 (king/piece shuffle move, no pawn push)
#   - Engine is materially down and Item-B clamps the endgame
#     ADV_PAWN_W bonus to zero (R9 = min(R9, preeg) wipes any
#     gain from advanced-pawn evaluation). All move options
#     therefore evaluate the same at preeg level (~-400 to -500)
#     and engine picks by move ordering, not by promotion gradient.
#
# Post-fix expected (Item-B promotion-survival, +ADV_PAWN_W/2
# applied AFTER the clamp):
#   - Engine sees a recovery signal proportional to advanced-pawn
#     presence. Two r6-class pawns contribute roughly +120 cp
#     (half of full r6 bonus 120 × 2 = 240).
#   - d=5 score should read LESS negative than -615 (the
#     promotion-survival bonus adds a constant to all moves but
#     the r6→r7 push specifically gains +40 cp via the gradient).
#   - Bestmove should ideally show a pawn-push move (e.g., b6b7
#     if available, or another rank-6 → rank-7 push).
#   - At minimum, bestmove should NOT be a king shuffle if a
#     promotable pawn push is legal.
#
# Caveat: the bonus is half-weight by design. If the noise floor
# (move-ordering bonuses, structural eval drift) is higher than
# the +40 cp gradient at this position, engine may still pick a
# non-push move. In that case we'd tune to 3/4 or full weight.

